A well-structured .gitignore file is crucial for maintaining a clean and efficient Git repository for your Next.js project. It prevents generated files, sensitive information, and local machine configurations from being unnecessarily committed to version control. Here is a comprehensive and standard .gitignore file for a typical Next.js application.

The .gitignore File
Create a file named .gitignore in the root of your Next.js project and add the following content:

Code snippet

# Dependencies
/node_modules
/.pnp
.pnp.js

# Build directory
/.next/
/out/

# Production build
/build

# Static exports
/export

# Cache
.eslintcache
.next-server-cache.json

# Environment variables
.env.local
.env.development.local
.env.test.local
.env.production.local
.env

# TypeScript
*.tsbuildinfo
tsconfig.tsbuildinfo

# Test reports
/coverage
/reports

# Editor directories and files
.vscode
.idea
*.suo
*.ntvs*
*.njsproj
*.sln
*.sw?

# Log files
npm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*
pnpm-debug.log*

# System files
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
